{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564586"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:15:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:15:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16991"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16991"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.73,0.11,0.06,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9681"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9681"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16991"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77702"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"3235"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31437"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by police after neighbours reported him shouting at people who were not there. He has a two-year history of schizophrenia and acknowledges having been unwell in the past, stating his previous hospitalisations were helpful. However, he believes his current experiences are different and related to genuine surveillance. He reports hearing voices but attributes them to government monitoring devices in his walls. He agrees to take medication \u0027to help with stress\u0027 but refuses antipsychotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears calm and cooperative. His pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His speech is coherent but contains references to being monitored. He states \u0027I know I have schizophrenia, but this situation is different - these are real threats, not symptoms. I\u0027ll take something for anxiety but I don\u0027t need antipsychotics because this isn\u0027t psychosis.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s level of insight?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete insight with treatment acceptance","Partial insight with selective symptom attribution","No insight with complete denial","Intellectual insight without emotional acceptance","Partial insight with treatment concordance"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a complex picture of insight in psychosis, demonstrating how insight can vary across different domains of illness experience. The patient shows a sophisticated but incomplete understanding of his condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial insight with selective symptom attribution\u003C/strong\u003E best describes this presentation. The patient acknowledges his diagnosis and past episodes of illness, showing some insight, but maintains fixed false beliefs about his current symptoms being \u0027different\u0027 and real. He can identify certain symptoms (hearing voices) but incorrectly attributes them to external causes rather than his illness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete insight with treatment acceptance\u003C/strong\u003E would require full awareness of current illness, correct attribution of all symptoms, and acceptance of appropriate treatment. While this patient shows some insight into his past illness, he lacks insight into his current situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo insight with complete denial\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the patient acknowledges his diagnosis and past episodes. He demonstrates partial rather than complete lack of insight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntellectual insight without emotional acceptance\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest the patient can discuss his condition abstractly but cannot apply this understanding emotionally. This patient shows more complex patterns of acceptance and denial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial insight with treatment concordance\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate the patient accepts appropriate treatment recommendations, which is not the case here as he specifically refuses antipsychotics while accepting other medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case illustrates how insight assessment in psychosis requires careful evaluation of multiple domains including historical awareness, current symptom attribution, and treatment attitudes. Patients may show varying levels of insight across different aspects of their illness experience.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complex insight assessment requires evaluation of multiple domains including illness awareness, symptom attribution, and treatment beliefs.","Insight in psychotic disorders exists on a spectrum and can vary across different aspects of illness experience.","Partial insight patterns can include acceptance of some symptoms while maintaining fixed false beliefs about others."],"references":["Sadock BJ, Sadock VA, Ruiz P. Kaplan and Sadock\u0027s comprehensive textbook of psychiatry. lippincott Williams \u0026 wilkins; 2017 May 11.","Markov\u00e1 IS, Berrios GE. Insight in clinical psychiatry: A new model. The Journal of nervous and mental disease. 1995 Dec 1;183(12):743-51."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77702"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16991"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77702"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-25T09:21:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-25T09:22:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9681"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"upd